item.title: AI recognition invlude but not limited to facial and voice cause serious health problem, 8th August
item.description:
Ultrasound is used in Neoface, other recognition, once connected to AI and biometrics, onky focus on the target. The dose will increase until it get the echo. Blocking dose not work. It caused ear pain, the dots in the picture is caused by the mechanical vibration and it is a standard test for ultrasonic cleaner bath for such vibration in clinic and hospitals. The mechanism of ear pain is just the vivration cause pain like very loud audible nose but the difference is not audible. Therefore others do not know the level of harm and do not feel it, ( focus to the person). Research papers related to AI recognition seldom talked about the dose, no safety data, only 1 showed 100 decibel but use object mimic the head. Even no test tube test, never check the safe limit and it is against human right in health, privacy up to torture inhuman degrading treatment. On Tuesday, 8 April 2025 at 16:43, Srinath NPL wrote: Dear Cecilia, We are not aware of any Ultrasound dose requirements in the area of facial recognition. In order to fully understand your question and to provide an appropriate response, we require the following information: After I gave them the figures and information. From: Srinath Rajagopal <srinath.rajagopal@npl.co.uk> Date: On Thursday, 10 April 2025 at 14:21 Subject: RE: Research enquiry from the NPL website Dear Cecilia, Thank you for providing the background information. NPL are only experts in Ultrasound that propagate in water or tissue-like medium. Your enquiry if of ultrasound radiated in-air. NPL lost all the air-borne acoustics capability in 2016, so we do not have any scientists with the expertise you require. I suggest you contacting University of Salford: https://www.salford.ac.uk/our-facilities/acoustics Best wishes Srinath RE: Cooperation with ICNIRP TO PROTECT US FROM ULTRASOUND 01:15Wednesday, 23 July 2025 at 01:15 Dear Cecilia Thank you for your enquiry to ARPANSA regarding the effects of airborne ultrasound. International guidance on airborne ultrasound was developed by the International Radiation Protection Association in 1984 and remains relevant for protection against environmental and occupational ultrasound currently. More recently the International Commission on Non-Ionizing Radiation Protection has published a statement on the validity of the 1984 guidelines. There is also a very good review on the health effects of ultrasound as well as infrasound by the Health Protection Agency in the UK. We encourage you to refer to these documents for a detailed explanation on the effects of ultrasound. Kind regards, Australian Radiation Protection and Nuclear Safety Agency Thursday, 8 May 2025 at 17:32, ccrpb / pcrpcc (HC/SC) <ccrpb-pcrpcc@hc-sc.gc.ca> wrote: Protected A / Protégé A Good afternoon, Dr Young, Thank you for your enquiry outlining your concerns for consumer electronic devices that emit ultrasound. We are aware of various such ultrasound devices and appreciate input from interested and engaged individuals. Radiation protection is a shared responsibility in Canada. Note unfortunately that the misuse of radiations is outside of the ICNIRP remit.
